# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: indiana-university
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] During the Gaza war and genocide, protests on university campuses in solidarity with the Palestinians in Gaza escalated in April 2024, spreading in the United States and other countries, as part of wider Gaza war protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The escalation, nicknamed by activists the "student intifada", began on April 18 after mass arrests at the Gaza Solidarity Encampment at Columbia University, in which protesters demanded the university's disinvestment from Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Over 3,100 protesters were arrested in the U.S., including faculty members and professors, on over 60 campuses.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests spread across Europe in May with mass arrests in the Netherlands, 20 encampments established in the United Kingdom, and across universities in Australia and Canada.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The different protests' varying demands included severing financial ties with Israel, transparency about financial ties, ending partnerships with Israeli institutions, and amnesty for protesters.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Universities suspended and expelled student protesters, in some cases evicting them from campus housing.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many universities relied on police to forcibly disband encampments and end occupations of buildings, several made agreements with protesters for encampments to be dismantled, and others cut ties with Israeli institutions or companies involved with Israel and its occupied territories.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The campus occupations also resulted in the closure of Columbia University, Cal Poly Humboldt, and the University of Amsterdam; rolling strikes by academic workers on campuses in California, and the cancellation of some U.S. university graduation ceremonies.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Hundreds of groups expressed support for the protests, and the police response in the U.S. was criticised.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Supporters of Israel and some Jewish students raised concerns about antisemitic incidents at or around the protests, prompting condemnations of the protests by international leaders.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students and faculty members who participated in the protests, many of whom are Jewish, said the protests were not antisemitic.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A May 2024 poll estimated that 8% of U.S. college students had participated in the protests, with 45% supporting them and 24% opposed.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 97% of the protests remained nonviolent and 28–40% of Americans supported the protests with 42–47% opposed.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests were compared to the anti-Vietnam and 1968 protests, politically criticized by a wide range of mainstream U.S.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Republican and Democratic politicians, and frequently counter-protested by Zionist and right-wing organizations.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests, including rallies, demonstrations, campaigns, and vigils related to the Gaza war occurred across the U.S. since the conflict's start on October 7, 2023, alongside other Gaza war protests around the world.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters criticized Israel's invasion, war conduct in the Gaza Strip, and U.S. military and diplomatic support for Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students occupying administrative buildings were arrested at the request of college administrators at Brown University in November and December 2023, and at Pomona College on April 5, 2024.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In March 2024, after protesters occupied the president's office at Vanderbilt University, the university suspended students and expelled three.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] These were "believed to be the first student expulsions over protests related to the Israel-Hamas conflict", according to *The New York Times*.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which was established to protect against racial discrimination in Jim Crow laws affecting education, was reinterpreted by Attorney Kenneth L.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Marcus while he was working at the Office for Civil Rights of the United States Department of Education to include protections against discrimination on the basis of religion, particularly "when an affected student's 'shared ancestry' would have been treated as a 'race' in earlier jurisprudence".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Jason Brownlee writes that Marcus "subsequently became one of the preeminent advocates for applying Title VI against speech and events criticizing Israeli repression of Palestinians, deeds Marcus considered antisemitic", and advocated adopting the IHRA definition of antisemitism.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On October 25, 2023, Jonathan Greenblatt of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and Alyza D.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Administrators at several private universities then suspended their SJP chapters, starting with Brandeis University on November 6, 2023.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On November 14, Columbia University followed suit, and also suspended its chapter of Jewish Voice for Peace.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The state of Florida ordered that all SJP chapters in the state be disbanded.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 6, 2024, student protests had occurred in 45 of the 50 states in the United States and the District of Columbia, with encampments, occupations, walkouts or sit-ins on almost 140 campuses.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Thirty-four encampments were established in the United Kingdom; across universities in Australia, beginning with the University of Sydney; and in Canada, including an encampment at McGill University.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 7, protests spread further on European campuses after mass arrests at the University of Amsterdam campus occupation, including occupation of campus buildings at Leipzig University in Germany, Sciences Po in France, and Ghent University in Belgium.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 8, protests had taken place in more than 25 countries, and on May 13, approximately 1,000 Dutch students and university staff took part in a national walk-out.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A series of occupation protests by pro-Palestinian students occurred at Columbia University in New York City from April to June 2024, in the context of the broader Gaza war protests in the United States.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests began on April 17, 2024, when pro-Palestinian students established an encampment of approximately 50 tents on campus, calling it the Gaza Solidarity Encampment, and demanded that the university divest from Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The first encampment was dismantled when university president Minouche Shafik authorized the New York City Police Department (NYPD) to enter the campus on April 18 and conduct mass arrests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A new encampment was built the next day.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The administration then entered into negotiations with protesters, which failed on April 29 and resulted in the suspension of student protesters.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next day, protesters broke into and occupied Hamilton Hall, leading to a second NYPD raid, the arrest of more than 100 protesters, and the full dismantling of the camp.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The arrests marked the first time Columbia had allowed police to suppress campus protests since the 1968 demonstrations against the Vietnam War.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 31, a third campus encampment was briefly established in response to an alumni reunion.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Other colleges that had encampments are marked in green, and non-encampment protests are marked in blue.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests emerged throughout the U.S. in the following days, with protest camps established on over 40 campuses.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 25, mass arrests occurred at Emerson College, the University of Southern California, and the University of Texas at Austin.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A continued crackdown on April 27 led to approximately 275 arrests at Washington, Northeastern, Arizona State, and Indiana University Bloomington.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Several professors were among those detained at Emory University, and at Washington University in St.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Louis, university employees were arrested.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 28, counter-protests were held at MIT, the University of Pennsylvania, and the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA).
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 30, approximately 300 protesters were arrested at Columbia University and City College of New York and pro-Israel counter-protesters attacked the UCLA campus occupation.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next day, over 200 arrests were made at UCLA.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Hundreds of arrests ensued in May, notably at the Art Institute of Chicago, University of California, San Diego, the Fashion Institute of Technology in New York, and University of California, Irvine.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 20, the first strike by academic workers took place on campuses in California at UC Santa Cruz, followed by UC Davis and UCLA on May 28.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests ended as universities closed for the summer.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many of the protests involved students demanding that their schools sever financial ties to Israel and companies involved in the conflict, as well as an end to U.S. military support for Israel, as part of the Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions (BDS) movement.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protests also demanded that universities sever academic ties with Israel, support a ceasefire in Gaza, and disclose investments.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student demands varied among the different occupations, including that universities stop accepting research money from Israel that supports the military, and that college endowments stop investing with managers who profit from Israeli entities.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student protesters called on Columbia University to financially divest from any company with business ties to the Israeli government, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] NYU Alumni for Palestine called on New York University to "terminate all vendor contracts with companies playing active roles in the military occupation in Palestine and ongoing genocide in Gaza, namely Cisco, Lockheed Martin, Caterpillar and General Electric".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters demanded that the University of Washington cut ties with Boeing.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at the University of Vermont demanded the cancellation of a planned commencement speech by Linda Thomas-Greenfield.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] After several mass arrests, the demands also included amnesty for students and faculty who were disciplined or fired for protesting.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The protests on many campuses were created by coalitions of student groups, and largely independent, although Reuters Press reported that they were inspired by demonstrations at Columbia University.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters at Vanderbilt University smashed a window and injured a security guard.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April 2024, the occupations resulted in the closure of Columbia University and Cal Poly Humboldt for the remainder of the semester, and faculty members in California, Georgia, and Texas also initiated votes of no confidence.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Columbia, Cal Poly Humboldt, and the University of Southern California canceled their graduation ceremonies due in May.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 13, the University of Amsterdam closed for two days after renewed occupations on campus.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] After demands from protesters, the University of Vermont canceled its graduation ceremony speaker, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations Linda Thomas-Greenfield.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On June 1, students staged a walkout at the University of Chicago's graduation ceremony, and walkouts at graduations occurred at Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, and elsewhere.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April, a pro-Palestinian student group won elections in the University of Michigan's student government.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In August, the student government voted to freeze its funding for student clubs until the university met student activists' divestment demands.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On April 28, Portland State University (PSU) announced it was pausing its financial ties with Boeing, including gifts and grants, over its ties to Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] PSU President Ann Cudd wrote in a campus-wide letter, "the passion with which these demands are being repeatedly expressed by some in our community motivates".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 6, Trinity College Dublin in Ireland agreed to end its investments in Israeli companies that are listed on the United Nations Human Rights Council "blacklist" after an encampment on Fellows' Square was erected.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] This included three of the 13 Israeli companies the university's endowment fund had invested in.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The University of Helsinki in Finland suspended student exchanges with Israeli universities on May 21 after two weeks of campus protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 28, the University of Copenhagen in Denmark announced it would cease investing in companies that operate in the occupied West Bank, divesting US$145,810 worth of holdings from Airbnb, Booking.com, and EDreams the next day.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Three days later, Ghent University in Belgium cut ties with Israeli universities and research institutions, referencing "concerns regarding connections between Israeli academic institutions and the Israeli government, military, or security services".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The university had severed ties with three Israeli institutions two weeks earlier, citing incompatibility with Israel's human rights policy.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On June 11, the University of Waterloo in Ontario, Canada, agreed to protesters' demands to factor human rights into its investment decisions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In late August 2024, San Francisco State University began the divestment process from four weapons manufacturers involved with the war.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The next month, the MIT Coalition for Palestine announced that MIT would discontinue its MIT-Lockheed Martin Seed Fund, a program that financed collaboration between MIT and Israeli universities.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Coalition said this was "the first known American-Israeli weapons manufacturer partnership to end at an American university since the war on Gaza began".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Three months later, the Institut d'études politiques de Strasbourg said it would break ties with Reichman University in Israel due to its "warmongering" stance on Gaza.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Other universities said they would consider divestment demands regarding Israel-affiliated companies.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some agreed to disclose their investments and committed to increase awareness about Palestine.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Wesleyan University allowed encampments on campus to continue, and at the University of Barcelona, the Senate voted to break ties with Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 15, the protest encampment at Harvard University ended after the administration agreed to discuss the protesters' demands and to rescind the suspension of 20 students.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At California State University, Sonoma State campus president Mike Lee was placed on leave after he agreed to pursue divestment from Israel "without the appropriate approvals".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 23, the University of Sydney became the first Australian university to accept certain demands.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The university agreed to further disclose research grants, subject to confidentiality requirements, in order to increase transparency.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at The New School attempted a unique strategy that combined escalations at their encampment and negotiations with administrators.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Rather than accepting that negotiations could continue only if escalation ceased, organizers escalated their protests and then offered to cease that escalation in exchange for other concessions during negotiations, improving their bargaining position.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Though police ultimately swept their encampment, the sweep led to backlash and condemnation by faculty and deans and required a day-long shutdown of the campus.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at The New School secured the formation of an advisory investment committee and a subsequent trustee vote on investment in the fall.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The authorization did not guarantee a strike, but allowed the executive board to call one at any time.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Strike action began at UC Santa Cruz on May 20.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Union members and leaders said they were not teaching or grading, were withholding data, and would continue to do so until they reached a deal with university officials.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The strike was in part a protest against arrests of pro-Palestinian protesters at UCLA, UC Irvine, and UC San Diego.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The UC system responded by seeking an injunction against the union, declaring the walkout illegal.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 23, the California Public Employment Relations Board denied the injunction.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The walkout extended to UCLA and UC Davis on May 28, with the intention of expanding to UC Santa Barbara, UC San Diego, and UC Irvine starting the week of June 3.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Participants included students, faculty, and unaffiliated people of various backgrounds, including Jews and Muslims.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian activists at Columbia said their movement is anti-Zionist, and several campus protests were organized by anti-Zionist groups.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some of the protests were organized by groups such as Students for Justice in Palestine (SJP), Jewish Voice for Peace, IfNotNow, and the Young Democratic Socialists of America.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters also identified a wide range of other ideologies that motivated them, such as anti-racism, intersectionality, anti-colonialism, anti-imperialism, police and prison abolitionism, eco-socialism, indigenous rights, and freedom of expression.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters also criticized President Joe Biden and his administration's support for Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] As part of the occupations, protesters hosted teach-ins, interfaith prayer, and musical performances.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protests invited people to tour or speak, such as Palestinian photojournalist Motaz Azaiza, who was invited to and visited Columbia's protest.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Palestinian activist Linda Sarsour said, "These young people are reaffirming and demonstrating that the tide is shifting on Palestine, that the Palestinian people have solidarity not just across the United States of America, but across the world".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Columbia, protesters who breached Hamilton Hall wrote revolutionary slogans (e.g., "Political power comes from the barrel of a gun") on blackboards.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One group involved in the protest movement, Columbia University Apartheid Divest, grew more supportive of armed resistance led by Hamas and the October 7 attacks over the course of 2024.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Within Our Lifetime leader Nerdeen Kiswani, who arrived at the Columbia encampment in April, called for Palestine liberation "'by any means necessary', including armed resistance".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Her group formed from CUNY SJP, which targeted the Brooklyn Museum in May 2024.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many anti-Zionist protesters donned masks and keffiyehs, which increased concerns from provosts and deans that outsiders had infiltrated protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protesters expressed fears of receiving reputational and professional harm from identification.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Concern was raised about the presence of outside groups at protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] During arrests in New York on May 2, police announced that nearly half of those arrested at Columbia and CCNY were unaffiliated with either school.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Mayor Eric Adams said that they had seen evidence that outside agitators and "professionals" such as Lisa Fithian and the wife of Sami Al-Arian had given students tactical knowledge and training to escalate their protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A University of Texas at Austin official said half of the rule breakers detained at a protest on April 24, 2024, were unaffiliated with the school.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In 2025, Swarthmore College said there was a "growing presence of individuals unaffiliated with the College" and campus property had been vandalized.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In October 2025, Syracuse University chancellor Kent Syverud said the protests on campus seemed to have been encouraged by Iran.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] He emphasized that, although there was an initially welcoming atmosphere for both pro-Israel and pro-Palestinian activities, a noticeable shift occurred later.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Syverud expressed his belief that Iran played a significant role in fostering the demonstrations, claiming that there was little to no involvement from the university's own students in the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Experts raised concern about far-right groups attempting to infiltrate protests to cause harm, and subsequent reactions from militant far-left activists aligned with the anti-fascist movement.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Qatar reportedly contributed $4.7 billion to U.S. academic institutions between 2001 and 2021; Kenneth Marcus of the Brandeis Center suggested this may have affected university administrators' willingness to impose discipline.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Far-right agitators and white nationalists were identified at some protests seeking to sow chaos and violence, and at the UCLA campus occupation, they were among pro-Israeli counter-protesters who attacked the encampment.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A white supremacist affiliated with the Proud Boys was among the counter-protesters supported by far-right activists nationwide.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On October 25, Jonathan Greenblatt of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) and Alyza D.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The website Canary Mission published profiles of students and faculty members it considers antisemitic, and Betar US, a Zionist group, compiled a list of students to be deported.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Several protests were criticized for alleged antisemitism.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some students called some of the incidents reported at protests and on campus "threatening" and said they made them feel unsafe.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Jewish students were targeted for their faith, for wearing Jewish symbols, or were accused of being Zionists and subsequently targeted.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some Jewish students also said the protests created a climate of fear and hate on campus.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to *The Jewish Post*, a survey by Hillel of Jewish students at universities with encampments found that most of them felt unsafe due to encampments.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 72% of respondents wanted them dismantled and 61% considered language used at the protests antisemitic.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Department of Education concluded that University of Michigan and CUNY failed to assess whether the protests made the environment hostile.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Supporters of Israel and some students said that the word "intifada", the phrase "from the river to the sea", and chants comparing Israel and Zionism to Nazism were antisemitic.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Others, including Jewish students, argued against conflating antisemitism with anti-Zionism, and said the charge was used to chill debate.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian and Jewish student protesters said that the protests were not antisemitic.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The Guardian* noted that incidents of antisemitism appeared to be "relatively isolated" and likelier to occur when non-students were in a parallel protest.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian student groups at the protests were quick to condemn inflammatory remarks.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some pro-Palestinian Jewish students said they faced antisemitism from pro-Israel activists.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some commentators and politicians, including Mayor Eric Adams, U.S.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Representative Virginia Foxx, and NYPD deputy commissioner of operations Kaz Daughtry, promoted a conspiracy theory that George Soros or some other anonymous figure funded the protest encampments by buying the same brand of tents for many protesters.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In fact, the similar appearance of many encampment tents was due to online retailers' discounts and promotions of particular products.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In fall 2024, chants such as "Divest!" and "Ceasefire now!" reportedly evolved towards more explicitly endorsing Hamas, Hezbollah, and Houthis.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some protesters used slogans such as "Glory to the resistance!", called the October 7 attacks "Al-Aqsa flood", celebrated Yahya Sinwar, and used the Hamas inverted red triangle.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Aidan Herzlinger, vice president of Baruch College's Hillel chapter, said students who attended a Hillel banquet at the college were called "baby killers" and "terrorists".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In November 2024, hundreds of posters depicting faculty members as "wanted" were spread across the University of Rochester campus.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some of the posters accused a Jewish faculty member of ethnic cleansing and contributing to the displacement of Palestinians; others accused a faculty member of racism, hate speech, and intimidation.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] University President Sarah Mangelsdorf called the incident an act of antisemitism.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian protesters and their allies criticized the disposition of many university administrations as perpetuating a "Palestine exception" to academic freedom.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Pro-Palestinian students and their allies raised concerns about anti-Palestinianism and Islamophobia.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Department of Education were opened at Columbia, Emory University, the University of North Carolina, and at Umass Amherst over their administrations' response to student protests and advocacy since the start of the war.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2024, the New York City Police Department shared images of items it said it had confiscated from a protest at NYU, including "gas masks, ear plugs, helmets, goggles, tape, hammers, knives, ropes, and a book on TERRORISM" that were taken from a student's backpack.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One pamphlet read, "Death to America!" According to the Anti-Defamation League, on the first anniversary of the October 7 attacks, many of the over 100 protests included chants and other messages "filled with support for terrorist organizations" and symbols such as paragliders.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Demonstrators at Columbia published a statement calling on students "to propagate the successes of the heroic Palestinian armed resistance in weakening Israel and U.S. imperialism and inspiring anti-imperialist struggles around the world".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A study by the Armed Conflict Location and Event Data Project (ACLED) found that 97% of protests were nonviolent and nearly half of those that became violent involved protesters fighting with law enforcement during police interventions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The guard was out of work for two weeks as a result of injuries.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The students denied using violence, calling their protest peaceful.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students and student journalists also faced violence at the hands of counter-protesters.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] One protester at Columbia was arrested and hospitalized after a counter-protester rammed his car into a group of picketers.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Counter-protesters at the University of Pennsylvania approached the encampment with knives, and in a separate incident sprayed a chemical mixture on protesters' tents, food, and belongings.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 1, 2024, around 10:50 PM, a pro-Israeli group attacked the University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) pro-Palestinian protesters' camp for nearly four hours, attempting to breach the barricades surrounding it.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The attackers, reported to have come from outside campus, carried Israeli flags and assaulted students with sticks, stones, poles, metal fencing, and pepper spray.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] They played loud audio of a child crying, threw wood and a metal barrier into the camp, and threw at least six fireworks into the encampment, including one directly at a group of protesters carrying injured people.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A video investigation suggested pro-Palestinian protesters did not initiate any confrontation but acted in defense.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The counter-protesters called for a "Second Nakba", referring to the ethnic cleansing of Palestinians in 1948, and played the Israeli national anthem and Harbu Darbu on loudspeakers during the attack.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to *The Guardian*, counter-protesters included several far-right activists involved in anti-LGBTQ+ and anti-vaccine campaigning.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Portland State, protesters damaged computers and furniture during their occupation of the campus library.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At Columbia, protesters shattered windows during their occupation of Hamilton Hall.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police and city workers destroyed students' tents, flags and other encampment supplies while disbanding the encampment at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] At George Washington University, protesters defaced a statue of its namesake, President George Washington.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The statue was wrapped with Palestinian scarves and flags, with the words "Genocidal Warmonger University" spray-painted on its base.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students replaced U.S. flags with Palestinian flags on flagpoles at several universities.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In Harvard Yard, student demonstrators affixed three Palestinian flags atop the John Harvard statue on April 27.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The replacement of U.S. flags sparked outrage from some officials, such as New York Mayor Eric Adams.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In response, university administrations and law enforcement agencies intervened to take down the Palestinian flags and reinstate U.S. flags to their original positions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] With over 3,100 protesters arrested, universities suspended and expelled student protesters, in some cases evicting them from campus housing, and relied on police to forcibly disband occupations.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Most universities that faced encampment protests in the spring attempted to negotiate a disbandment of the encampments, often threatening police sweeps to force an agreement.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Many universities initiated disciplinary proceedings against protesters, accusing them of breaking student codes of conduct.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In July 2025, Columbia University disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests with probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police departments employed a range of tactics, including dispersing crowds using horses and police in riot gear, deploying pepper balls, using tasers, mass arrests, and tear gas, clearing unauthorized encampments, and beating both students and professors.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Police also assaulted, arrested and restricted access for some journalists while they were covering the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Some Democrats and human rights organizations criticized the police response.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By fall 2024, many universities had strengthened their restrictions on protests, including more than 100 colleges and universities, and several schools had banned camping on their grounds.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Over 200 groups expressed support for the protests, as well as U.S.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Senator Bernie Sanders, various members of Congress, several labor unions, hundreds of university staff in the United Kingdom, and Iran's supreme leader Ali Khamenei.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Protests were condemned by leaders including President Joe Biden, Prime Minister of the Netherlands Mark Rutte, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, and Australian Prime Minister Anthony Albanese.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak and Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau raised concerns.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Numerous U.S. corporate leaders announced that they wished to know the protesters' names in order to prevent them from working in their firms.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Among them were Davis Polk & Wardwell, Pershing Square Capital Management, shopping club FabFitFun, health tech startup EasyHealth, Dovehill Capital Management, and restaurant chain Sweetgreen.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A May 2024 divestment referendum at DePaul University returned a 91% vote in favor of divestment.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In April 2024, Columbia College voted on three divestment questions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The first asked whether Columbia should divest from Israel, the second asked whether it should cancel the Tel Aviv Global Center program, and the third asked whether Columbia should end its dual degree program with Tel Aviv University.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The motions passed by 76%, 68%, and 65%, respectively, with 40% voter participation.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students at the University of Pennsylvania voted 73% in favor of disclosing all investments in the school's endowment and 63% in favor of ending the university's relationship with Ghost Robotics, with 22% voter participation.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to a YouGov poll released on May 3, 2024, 47% of Americans opposed the campus protests and 28% supported them.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] American Muslims supported the protests by 75% to 14% while Jewish Americans opposed them by 72% to 18%.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Adults under 45 were more likely to support them than older adults.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 33% believed the response to the protests was not harsh enough, 16% believed it was too harsh, and 20% believed the response was about right.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 48% of Americans over 45 believed the response was not harsh enough, compared to only 16% under 45.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to an Axios poll released on May 7, 2024, 8% of college students participated in the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 34% blame Hamas, 19% blame Netanyahu, 12% blame the Israeli people, and 12% blame Biden for the destruction in Gaza.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] 81% of students supported holding protesters accountable for destroyed property and illegally occupied buildings, 67% considered occupying campus buildings unacceptable, 58% considered refusal to disperse unacceptable, and 90% opposed blocking pro-Israel students.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Students were more likely to support the pro-Palestinian encampments, with 45% who supported them strongly or moderately, 30% neutral, and 24% strongly or mildly opposed.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Among those who participated in anti-Israeli protests, 58% said they would not be friends with someone who had marched for Israel, while 64% of students who marched in favor of Israel said they would still be friends with anti-Israeli protesters.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Overall, 40% approved and 42% disapproved of the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In Canada, 19% of respondents supported the protesters and 48% of respondents opposed the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The New York Times* reported that some scholars considered the protests starkly different from those against the Vietnam War or apartheid South Africa.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to Timothy Naftali, protests against Vietnam in the 1960s did not result in a constituency that felt attacked as an ethnicity, and that the pro-Palestinian demonstrations created "a feeling of insecurity in a much bigger way than the antiwar demonstrations during Vietnam did".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft said current college protests contain "further echoes of the forces that helped give rise to the Nazis", while Columbia University's Chabad chapter said that phrases like "Go back to Poland" and "stop killing children" had been yelled at Jewish students.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2024, some Jewish students on campus said they believed that support for Israel was a "litmus test" leading to their exclusion from campus social life.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In September 2024, after many harassment complaints, the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign banned the ostracism of Jewish students from school clubs for identifying as Zionist.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Far-right influencers and some Republicans portrayed the protests as violent, a "Marxist takeover," and "terrorism".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] *The New York Times* opined that the protests came during a presidential election year in which Democrats had "harnessed promises of stability and normalcy to win critical recent elections" and that the protests were a messaging opportunity for Republicans to divide Democrats.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The newspaper also published an article citing NewsGuard, the Institute for Strategic Dialogue, the Foundation for Defense of Democracies, the Australian Strategic Policy Institute, and Recorded Future on how the media of Russia, China, and Iran had covered the events.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] It concluded that those countries had made overt and covert efforts to capitalize on the protests to denigrate democracy, inflame partisan tensions, criticize Biden ahead of the 2024 presidential election, support Trump, and express support for Hamas and Palestinians generally.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] A *Jewish Currents* editor described the movement as providing "cover for the right to expand its attack on protest" in reference to the "draconian" crackdown on protests, saying the "attacks on academic freedom and free speech on campus" were led by right-wingers.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Republicans used antisemitic tropes when denouncing protests as antisemitic, including allusions to conspiracies around George Soros and invoking globalists.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] In May 2025, *The New York Times* found that the second Trump administration had called for or implemented over half the proposals of The Heritage Foundation's Project Esther, a conservative program to suppress pro-Palestinian protests and what it classifies as antisemitism.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Initially, *The New York Times* wrote that protests outside the U.S. were "sporadic and smaller, and none [started] a wider student movement".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The "partisan political context" was given as a reason for the intensity of protests in the U.S.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Columbia's status as an Ivy League school, its proximity to New York City and national news media, and its large population of Jewish students were described as fueling increased media attention and political scrutiny that helped spread the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to a *Washington Monthly* study in May, pro-Palestinian demonstrations and encampments were more prevalent at elite U.S. universities.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] On May 3, NPR described the protests abroad as "a growing global student movement", with student protests in the United Kingdom focused on "an increasingly high-profile nationwide campaign to end British arms exports to Israel".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] According to NBC News, the protests abroad inspired by protests in the U.S. did not have the intensity of U.S. protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 7, protests had escalated in Europe after mass arrests at the University of Amsterdam, with occupations of campus buildings in Germany, France, and Belgium, and encampments on several European campuses.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The Associated Press described protests at Sciences Po in Paris as "echoing similar encampments and solidarity demonstrations across the United States".
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] By May 9, protests were widespread at universities in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, while smaller ones were held at Japanese and South Korean universities.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Media coverage of the protests was criticized as sensationalized and failing to focus on the protesters' demands and grievances.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Dana Bash was criticized for likening college protests to the rise of antisemitism in the 1930s in Europe.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] The lack of student protesters' voices in most national media coverage was also criticized.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p01] Student reporters, in particular, were praised for their work covering the protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The global wave of student- and staff-led demonstrations on university campuses continued in 2025, with protests at hundreds of campuses in North America, Europe, Australia, Africa, and Asia.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Inspired by the anti-apartheid and Vietnam War campus protests, students and faculty called for divestment, academic boycott, and institutional transparency about ties to Israel and military contractors.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The movement intensified in 2025 after Israel's offensive in Rafah and renewed violence in Gaza, as well as solidarity actions in response to police crackdowns on US campuses.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the United States, at Columbia University, there were renewed encampments and building occupations, including the occupation of Butler Library ("Basel Al-Araj Popular University").
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] There were mass arrests by the NYPD and over 100 students were suspended or barred from campus.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In July 2025, Columbia disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests, with punishments including probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] At the University of Washington, protesters occupied an engineering building, demanding an end to ties with Boeing over its military contracts.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] More than 30 protesters were arrested after police intervention.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Thirty-four people were arrested inside the School of Engineering building and over $1 million in damage was done to the structure.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Canada, after a three-day student protest that included blockades and vandalism, the Quebec Superior Court issued a 10-day injunction barring pro-Palestinian protesters at McGill University from obstructing campus access or disrupting academic activities.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Citing threats to safety and academic continuity, McGill sought legal intervention amid calls for divestment from companies linked to Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] It has also initiated steps to sever ties with the undergraduate student union over its alleged failure to distance itself from disruptive activism.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Germany, Berlin police cleared a protest in April 2025 at Humboldt University, where 89 pro-Palestinian demonstrators had occupied a lecture hall to oppose the planned deportation of four international students accused of participating in violent protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The police launched around 100 criminal investigations related to the occupation, citing vandalism, use of incendiary objects, and alleged extremist symbols.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university justified police intervention partly due to banners denying Israel's right to exist, an issue sensitive in Germany due to its post-Holocaust commitment to supporting Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Germany is facing criticism for issuing orders to deport four pro-Palestinian activists who have been convicted of no crimes.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the Netherlands there were occupations and encampments at the University of Amsterdam, Utrecht University, Radboud University, and others.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Several protests were met with police intervention, with students sustaining injuries.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the United Kingdom, members of Oxford Action for Palestine occupied the Radcliffe Camera, protesting the alleged complicity of the University of Oxford in Israeli military actions in Gaza and the West Bank and accusing the institution of cutting off dialogue.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university condemned the disruption, citing safety concerns, and said it was working to remove the protesters, who had renamed the library after a Palestinian political figure linked to a group several Western governments have designated a terrorist organization.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] At the University of Glasgow, students from the Justice for Palestine Society disrupted campus events in April, calling for divestment from arms companies accused of complicity in what they describe as genocide in Gaza.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Across the UK, over 100 students and staff have faced disciplinary action, with some universities reportedly working with private intelligence firms to monitor protests.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Many universities called on police to clear encampments and occupations, resulting in mass arrests and suspensions of students and faculty.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Some institutions agreed to partial demands, including publishing lists of ties to Israeli entities or freezing select partnerships.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The US government threatened funding cuts to universities that did not address alleged antisemitism or campus unrest, and some protesters faced deportation proceedings.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] Civil liberties groups and faculty organizations expressed concern over free speech, academic freedom, and the militarization of campus policing.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In July 2025, Columbia University disciplined at least 70 students who took part in campus protests, with punishments including probation, suspensions, degree revocations, and expulsions.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Canada, after pro-Palestinian protests at the University of Toronto and a more than 60-day encampment on its St.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] George campus, the University of Toronto Faculty Association (UTFA) voted to divest from Israel, citing its opposition to what it called Israel's "illegal occupation" of Palestinian territories.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The motion, which passed with 52% support, urges the Ontario University Pension Plan to swiftly divest from entities linked to the occupation or arms production potentially used by Israel in Palestine, aligning the move with the university’s existing divestment policy on Russia.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the Netherlands, the University of Amsterdam, Tilburg University, Utrecht University, Erasmus University Rotterdam, and Radboud University have cut ties with nine Israeli institutes, with some also suspending future collaborations.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In the UK, King’s College Cambridge announced divestment from arms and companies involved in the Israeli occupation.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] In Ireland, Trinity College Dublin severed all ties with Israeli universities and companies, becoming the first Irish university to fully divest.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] This includes ending investments, commercial relations, academic collaborations, and Erasmus+ exchanges.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The move follows a taskforce review and a five-day student encampment protesting the college's ties to Israel.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The university had investments in 13 Israeli companies, some linked to illegal settlements.
[src:indiana-university/2024-pro-palestinian-protests-on-university-campuses-p02] The decision was praised by student leaders and politicians, who called it a model for other institutions to follow.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] Aaron Waltke was born and raised in Greenwood, Indiana and spent some of his childhood on the islands of Sanibel-Captiva in the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He attended Indiana University Bloomington, where he initially studied Psychology until he began directing live theatre, performing sketch comedy, and writing screenplays.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He moved to Los Angeles, where his work was shown at venues including The Upright Citizens Brigade Theatre, iO West, The Comedy Store, and the L.A.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] Waltke began his television career producing and directing documentaries for PBS affiliate WTIU.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] After moving to Los Angeles, he was hired by *The National Lampoon* as a writer and producer to create original content.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2012, he was hired to write a live-action feature film adaptation of *The Brave Little Toaster*.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He was later hired to adapt a live action feature film version of the popular comic strip *Heathcliff* for the same company.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He became a showrunner and co-executive producer on the final installment of the franchise, *Wizards: Tales of Arcadia*, for which he co-wrote the pilot with Guillermo del Toro.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He was nominated for an Emmy Award in the category of "Outstanding Children's Animated Series" and won a Kidscreen Award for "Best New Series".
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2017, he served as a head writer for the Cartoon Network spinoff of *The Lego Movie* entitled *Unikitty!* produced by Warner Bros.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] While there, he co-wrote an episode of *Teen Titans Go!* for the same creative team.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In July 2019, Waltke joined the television show *Star Trek: Prodigy* as a writer and producer, later co-executive producer and co-head writer for the series.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He previously collaborated with the show's creators, The Hageman Brothers, on *Trollhunters.* In 2022, he was nominated for an Emmy Award for "Outstanding Animated Series" for his work on the show.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2023 and 2025, his work was twice nominated for a Television Critics Association Award in the category of "Outstanding Achievement in Family Programming." In 2024, his and others' contributions to *Star Trek* were honored with a Peabody Institutional Award.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In October 2020, Legion M announced that Waltke was attached to develop and executive produce an adult animated feature film with Powerhouse Animation based on George Mann's *Ghosts of Manhattan* novels, an action sci-fi noir story set in an alternate history 1920s New York.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2023, Waltke was hired to develop the story and script for the feature film *Transformers One,* a prequel film in the *Transformers* franchise.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2025, Waltke was announced as showrunner, executive producer, and head writer for Amazon Prime Video's television adaptation of the bestselling fantasy series *Wings of Fire*.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2023, Waltke was announced as a writer for DC Comics in the anthology, *How to Lose a Guy Gardner in 10 Days.* The collection explores the strange world of superhero romance in the DC Universe.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2025, Waltke became co-writer of Stan Lee's *The Excelsiors*, a graphic novel series based on Lee's final unpublished works set in an original superhero universe.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] In 2025, Waltke was a finalist in *Mystery Writers of America*’s annual “Six Word Murder Mystery” contest.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] His story was published in the March/April 2026 issue of *Alfred Hitchcock’s Mystery Magazine*.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] Waltke is married to fellow writer and published mystery author Ellen Tremiti.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] Waltke engages in youth activism and outreach.
[src:indiana-university/aaron-waltke] He was the keynote speaker at the 2018 RESET Technology & Creativity Conference, a bi-national event between El Paso, Texas, and Ciudad Juárez, Chihuahua, aimed at encouraging youth innovation, creativity, and opportunity across the Mexico–US border.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] Basu was born in Calcutta (now Kolkata), India.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He is the eldest son of painter Atul Bose.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He received his B.Sc. in geology from Calcutta's Presidency College (now Presidency University, Kolkata) and M.Sc. from the Calcutta University.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He worked as a geologist for the Geological Survey of India for about ten years.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] A Fulbright program grant enabled him to move to the USA.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He got his Ph.D. in 1975 from Indiana University Bloomington and was a post-doctoral researcher at Harvard University and NASA.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He has been teaching at Indiana University since 1979 where he is an emeritus professor in Indiana University's Department of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He is married to Ilora Basu and is the father of musician Joy Basu.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] Basu's academic contributions include studying differences in rock formation on Earth, the Moon, and Mars, among others.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He has guided many Ph.D. dissertations and masters thesis.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] He has served as an officer in scholarly bodies and has been an associate editor for many scholarly publications.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] The Geological Society of America (GSA) gave its highest service award to Basu in 2006.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] The award recognized him as a scientist who has "received many national and international awards and honors and is the creator of a large body of work and publications." The award specifically acknowledged his contributions to expansion of the society's publications program.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] The number of books published by the GSA has doubled during Basu's 10-year editorial term.
[src:indiana-university/abhijit-basu] Basu has received Distinguished Service Awards from Indiana University Bloomington and the North American Bengali Conference.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Tenure was introduced into American universities in the early 1900s in part to prevent the arbitrary dismissal of faculty members who expressed unpopular views.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Before Nazism, Germany had been a leader in academic tenure, but free speech and tenure were severely curtailed under the Third Reich.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Adolf Hitler called universal education "the most corroding and disintegrating poison".
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] He appointed Education Minister Bernhard Rust, to ensure Nazi racial theories were integrated in university curriculums.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] This caused a purge of 1500 professors, and by 1939, nearly half of all faculty posts were occupied by Nazis.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] In the late 1940s, the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign fired several untenured economists, all of whom subsequently had distinguished careers, for teaching the "heresy" Keynesian economics.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Danish universities in advertisements for faculty positions usually state that professor positions are tenured.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] What that means has been a matter of controversy.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Denmark adopted a more hierarchical management approach for universities in the early 2000s.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] This new system was introduced by parliament on a proposal by the Minister of Science, Technology and Development, Helge Sander, based on his vision that Danish universities should compete for funding in order to increase their attention to marketing and industry.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Thybo disputed the causes of his firing, and the postdoc said that he did not feel pressured.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] The handling of the firing was criticized by other researchers.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] A later court decision ruled that the dismissal had not followed the collective agreements and Thybo received economic compensation.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Thybo had insisted that he should be reinstated in his previous position, but this was not supported by the court and the university did not rehire him.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] The original form of academic tenure was removed in the United Kingdom in 1988 through the Education Reform Act.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] In its place, there is the distinction between permanent and temporary contracts for academics.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] A permanent lecturer in UK universities usually holds an open-ended position that covers teaching, research and administrative responsibilities.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] In 2010, 9% of academic staff were professors, 66% were "junior staff" (including doctoral candidates on contracts), and 25% were other academic staff in secondary employment.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Permanent research, teaching and management positions below professorship as an "Akademischer Rat" (a civil service position salaried like high school teachers) have become relatively rare compared to the 1970s and 1980s and are often no longer refilled after a retirement.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] This means that, compared to other countries, academics in Germany obtain tenure at a relatively late age, as on average one becomes an Academic Assistant at the age of 42.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] In 2002 the "Juniorprofessur" position (comparable to an assistant professor in the US, but not always endowed with a tenure track) was introduced as an alternative to "Habilitation".
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Due to a university system that guarantees universities relative academic freedom, the position of professor in Germany is relatively strong and independent.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] As civil servants, professors have a series of attendant rights and benefits, yet this status is subject to discussion.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] In the W pay scale the professorial pay is related to performance rather than merely to age, as it was in C.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Under the tenure systems adopted by many universities and colleges in the United States and Canada, some faculty positions have tenure and some do not.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] This statement holds that, "The common good depends upon the free search for truth and its free exposition" and stresses that academic freedom is essential in teaching and research in this regard.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] The statement limits the number of years that any employee can remain employed as a non-tenured instructor or professor, compelling the institution to grant tenure to or terminate an individual, with significant advance notice, at the end of a specified time period.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Some institutions require promotion to associate professor as a condition of tenure.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] A university may also offer research positions or professional track and clinical track academic positions which are said to be "non-tenure track".
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Positions with titles such as instructor, lecturer, adjunct professor, research professor etc. do not carry the possibility of tenure, have higher teaching loads, have less influence within the institution, lower compensation with few or no benefits and little protection of academic freedom.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] In the United States, tenure rights for teachers serving in K-12 public schools also have been in existence for more than a hundred years, beginning first in New Jersey in 1909..
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Defenders of tenure, like Ellen Schrecker and Aeon J.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] "Tenure remains scholars' best defense of free inquiry and heterodoxy," writes Skoble, "especially in these times of heightened polarization and internet outrage.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Moreover, there is no way that the employing institution can provide the kind of retraining that would facilitate such a transformation... even the largest and most well-endowed institution lacks the resources to reevaluate and replace its medieval Islamicists and algebraic topologists every year.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Tenure thus lets the academic community avoid excessive turnover while still ensuring the quality of the institution's faculty.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] To Bruce, this is an argument against tenure, but my point is that the more I am persuaded that there is groupthink orthodoxy afoot, the more I want assurances that I would not get fired if I write an essay on free trade or the Second Amendment or a book on anarchism.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] I take it the counterargument is that the more entrenched the orthodoxy becomes, the less likely a heterodox scholar will be tenured, or even hired, in the first place...
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] I can see that this poses a problem but fail to see how abolishing tenure would help.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] As things stand, some heterodox scholars do get hired and tenured..
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Skoble argues categorically and plainly against critics that say "tenure protects incompetent professors": "My argument is that when this happens, it is a malfunction of the system, not an intrinsic feature of its proper use.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] The way it is supposed to work is that incompetent professors do not get tenure in the first place.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Some have argued that modern tenure systems diminish academic freedom, forcing those seeking tenured positions to profess conformance to the level of mediocrity as those awarding the tenured professorships.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Economist Steven Levitt, who recommends the elimination of tenure (for economics professors) in order to incentivize higher performance among professors, also points out that a pay increase may be required to compensate faculty members for the lost job security.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Organizational theorist Russel Ackoff did not believe in it, and went as far as to deposit a signed but undated resignation letter with the Dean of the Wharton School, to be used if and when the Dean thought it could be appropriate to do so.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Some U.S. states have considered legislation to remove tenure at public universities.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] A further criticism of tenure is that it rewards complacency.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Once professors are awarded tenure, they may begin putting reduced effort into their job, knowing that their removal is difficult or expensive to the institution.
[src:indiana-university/academic-tenure] Another criticism is that it may cause the institution to tolerate incompetent professors if they are tenured.
[src:indiana-university/administrator-of-the-united-states-agency-for-international-development] The **administrator of the United States Agency for International Development** is the head of the United States federal government's Agency for International Development (USAID).
[src:indiana-university/administrator-of-the-united-states-agency-for-international-development] The administrator is officially nominated by the president of the United States and confirmed by the United States Senate.
[src:indiana-university/administrator-of-the-united-states-agency-for-international-development] A 2017 reorganization of the US National Security Council placed the USAID administrator as a permanent member on the Deputies Committee.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Agnes Nebo von Ballmoos was born in Grand Cess in Grand Kru County.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Nebo and her mother was Grace Nah Tameh Nebo.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] As a child, she attended the Bible Industrial Academy in Grand Bassa County and Suehn Mission School in Bomi County.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] She received a scholarship for academic excellence to complete her high school studies at Nannie Helen Burroughs School in Washington, D.C.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Von Ballmoos received an undergraduate degree in piano performance in 1959 from the Philadelphia Conservatory of Music.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] In 1975, she completed a master's degree in ethnomusicology from Indiana University, which she attended on a Fulbright fellowship.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Her master's thesis examined the social role of folk songs in Liberia.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Shortly after completing her undergraduate degree, Agnes married Rudolph von Ballmoos, with whom she had two sons.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Their elder son, also named Rudolph, served as Liberia's ambassador to the United Kingdom.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Their younger son, DeWitt von Ballmoos, leads Liberia's National Social Security and Welfare Corporation.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] From 1961 to 1990, von Ballmoos taught music at the University of Liberia, where she was a founding member of the music program.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] She also conducted the University of Liberia choir.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Von Ballmoos introduced traditional Liberian music into the choir's repertoire for the first time.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] "Our research began in 1966 with the arrangement of seven songs performed by the University of Liberia choir--the very first time in our history of indigenous songs being performed by our highest institution.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] The idea thrilled the entire community and we received encouraging letters of congratulations and compliments," she wrote.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Under her direction, the choir gained international attention for its performances, which included a mixture of classical music, African-American spirituals, and traditional Liberian songs.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] The group gave concerts around the world, including a 1974 performance at an international choral festival at Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts in New York City.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] It was the only group representing an African country to participate in the festival.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Von Ballmoos preserved, transcribed, and recorded folk music from across Liberia's diverse cultural traditions.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] She was a pioneer in the transcription of Liberian folk songs into written form.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] She also created original arrangements of traditional songs.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] In 1989, von Ballmoos received a Bachelor of Laws degree from the University of Liberia and became a lawyer at a Monrovia law firm.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] To escape the First Liberian Civil War, she moved to London in 1990.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] There, she worked as a legal consultant.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] The University of Liberia Alumni Chorus, founded in 2009, performs an annual concert in the United States to celebrate von Ballmoos' legacy and raise money for the music department at the University of Liberia.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] The 2019 performance took place in Battell Chapel at Yale University.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Von Ballmoos' work also significantly contributed to the preservation of Liberian folk music.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] In the 1960s and 1970s, when von Ballmoos began her career, traditional music was not highly valued.
[src:indiana-university/agnes-nebo-von-ballmoos] Her efforts helped increase appreciation of traditional music and culture.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In college at Indiana University he was a unanimous selection as the 2010 Big Ten Conference Baseball Player of the Year.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson was drafted by the Pittsburgh Pirates in the third round of the 2011 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He was the 2012 Florida State League Player of the Year, 2013 Eastern League Rookie of the Year, and 2015 Pacific Coast League Rookie of the Year.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He made his MLB debut with the San Diego Padres in 2015.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He underwent Tommy John surgery in 2018.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson played for Team Israel in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson attended Poway High School in Poway, California, and played on the baseball team as a first baseman and outfielder.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He batted .354/.420/.686 as a junior, .455/.522/.851 as a senior, and was named All-San Diego Division I Player of the Year.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] At the age of fifteen Dickerson underwent back surgery, and first became known by the nickname Grandpa.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] The Washington Nationals selected Dickerson in the 48th round of the 2008 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He elected, however, to attend Indiana University, where he played outfield and designated hitter for the Indiana Hoosiers baseball team from 2009 to 2011.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] As a freshman, batting cleanup, Dickerson hit .370/.428/.618 with 14 home runs.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He was named the Big Ten Conference's Freshman of the Year and received Freshman All-American honors.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson had a breakout season as a sophomore, slugging .805 (8th in the nation) and winning the Big Ten Triple Crown by leading the Big Ten in batting average (.419), home runs (24; second in the nation), and runs batted in (75).
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He was named the Big Ten Conference Baseball Player of the Year, and earned first-team All-American honors.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In 2009 and 2010, he played collegiate summer baseball with the Wareham Gatemen of the Cape Cod Baseball League.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] The Pittsburgh Pirates selected Dickerson in the third round of the 2011 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] After signing for a signing bonus of $380,700, Dickerson spent most of the rest of the 2011 season with the State College Spikes, batting .313/.393/.493 with an .886 OPS (9th in the New York-Pennsylvania League) in 150 at bats; his 16 doubles were second among all short-season batters.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson spent the 2012 season with the Bradenton Marauders, where he batted .295/.353/.451 with 31 doubles (4th in the league), 13 home runs (7th), and 90 RBIs (2nd) in 488 at bats and was named the Florida State League Player of the Year, a post-season All Star, and an MiLB organization All Star.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Prior to the 2013 season, Dickerson was named the 7th-best first base prospect in baseball by MLB.com.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He spent 2013 with the Double-A Altoona Curve, where he moved from first base to the outfield.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He batted .288/.337/.494 with 36 doubles (2nd in the league), 17 home runs, and 68 RBIs in 451 at bats and was named the Eastern League Rookie of the Year, a post-season All Star, and an MiLB organization All Star.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On November 25, 2013, the Pirates traded Dickerson to the San Diego Padres for Jaff Decker and Miles Mikolas.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson sprained his left ankle in 2014 spring training with the Padres when he stepped on a sprinkler head, and an MRI later found a bone cyst in his left heel which required surgery and a bone graft.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] The surgery delayed his start to the 2014 season, but he finished with 34 games with the Double-A San Antonio Missions, batting .321/.367/.496 in 137 at bats.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On November 20, 2014, the Padres added Dickerson to their 40-man roster to protect him from the Rule 5 draft.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson spent most of 2015 with the Triple-A El Paso Chihuahuas, hitting .307 (10th in the league)/.374/.503 with 82 runs (3rd), 36 doubles (6th), 9 triples (2nd), 12 home runs, and 71 RBIs in 459 at bats over 125 games, including 88 starts in left field.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] His performance earned him the Pacific Coast League Rookie of the Year Award, and he was named a post-season All Star and an MiLB organization All Star.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On August 6, 2015, Dickerson made his Major League debut with the San Diego Padres with a pinch-hitting appearance in the 8th inning.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He was called up to replace Will Venable, who went on paternity leave.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] The next day, Dickerson collected his first Major League hit with a pinch single in extra innings.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson returned to the Padres when rosters expanded in September.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] A tweaked hip flexor limited his playing opportunities, but Dickerson appeared in eight more games as a pinch hitter, and once as a defensive substitute in left field.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson started the 2016 season in Triple-A El Paso.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On May 2, the Padres recalled Dickerson from Triple-A.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On May 10 against the Chicago Cubs at Wrigley Field, Dickerson hit a pinch-hit grand slam off of Adam Warren for his first career home run and his first four career RBIs.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He made his first Major League start in left field the following day, but was returned to El Paso on May 14.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] With the Chihuahuas, he continued a 28-game minor league hitting streak through the end of May.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On June 28, Dickerson was recalled from El Paso when Jon Jay broke his forearm.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson remained as the regular left fielder for the Padres for the remainder of the season.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] For the season, with El Paso he batted .382/.425/.622 with 10 home runs and 51 RBIs in 217 at bats.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He finished the season with the Padres with a .257/.333/.455 batting line and 39 runs, 10 home runs, and 37 RBIs in 285 plate appearances.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In spring training of 2017, Dickerson suffered a bulging disk.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] After initially trying to rehab the injury, Dickerson underwent back surgery by microdiscectomy to remove bulging disc material in his lower back which ended his season.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In spring training of 2018, while trying to come back from his back surgery, Dickerson tore his UCL in his elbow and underwent Tommy John surgery, costing him another full season.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He was outrighted off the roster after the season.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He elected free agency on November 3, 2018, and later re-signed to a minor league deal on December 11.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Playing for AAA El Paso in 2019, he hit .372/.469/.606 with 5 home runs and 20 RBIs in 94 at bats.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson had his contract selected to the major leagues on May 3, 2019, but after 19 at bats with the Padres was designated for assignment on June 5.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On June 10, 2019, Dickerson was traded to the San Francisco Giants in exchange for Franklin van Gurp, one of the first trades with new Giants general manager Farhan Zaidi.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He played seven games for the Triple-A Sacramento River Cats.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On June 21, in his first game with the Giants, he hit a grand slam and had a career-high 6 runs batted in.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On September 1, 2020, Dickerson had a historic game which came as part of a 23–5 victory against the Rockies at Coors Field.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He went 5–6 with 3 home runs and 2 doubles and tied the franchise records for runs scored (5) and total bases (16) in a game.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] His double in his last at bat traveled 414 feet and would have been a home run in any other MLB ballpark; thus he fell just short of tying Willie Mays' 4 home runs in a single game.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He played 41 games in left field, and 5 games in right field.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Avoiding arbitration, Dickerson and the Giants agreed on a $2.1 million salary for the 2021 season.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] During the season, he was on the injured list three times, with right shoulder, upper back, and right hamstring issues.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In the 2021 regular season, he batted .233/.304/.420 with a career-high 13 home runs and 38 RBIs in 283 at bats.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He played 82 games in left field, and his range factor per 9 innings of 1.78 was the fifth-best in the National League.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On November 22, 2021, Dickerson was designated for assignment by the Giants to make room for pitcher Anthony DeSclafani.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On November 26, 2021, he was placed on unconditional release waivers.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On March 16, 2022, Dickerson signed a non-guaranteed, major-league contract worth $1 million with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] The Braves designated Dickerson for assignment on April 28.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Two days later, Dickerson was outrighted to the Gwinnett Stripers, for whom he batted .239/.305/.426 with 12 home runs and 43 RBIs in 322 at bats, playing 40 games in right field and 20 games in left field.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He had four hits in 43 at bats for the Braves.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On October 17, Dickerson elected free agency.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On April 8, 2023, Dickerson signed with the Acereros de Monclova of the Mexican League.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson was released by Monclova on May 5.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On May 12, 2023, Dickerson signed with the Long Island Ducks of the Atlantic League of Professional Baseball.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In 115 games for the Ducks, Dickerson hit .314/.389/.576 with career–highs in home runs (26) and RBI (91).
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On December 22, 2023, Dickerson signed with the Chunichi Dragons of Nippon Professional Baseball.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] In 32 games for Chunichi in 2024, slashing .205/.314/.352 with three home runs and five RBI.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On October 26, 2024, the Dragons announced they would not bring Dickerson back for the 2025 season, making him a free agent.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] On June 18, 2025, Dickerson signed with the High Point Rockers of the Atlantic League of Professional Baseball.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson played for Team Israel in the 2023 World Baseball Classic in Miami, in March 2023.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] He played for Team Israel manager and former All-Star Ian Kinsler, and alongside All-Star outfielder Joc Pederson and pitcher Dean Kremer, among others.
[src:indiana-university/alex-dickerson] Dickerson and his wife Jennifer had a son in September 2020.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The School of Medicine and the School of Social Work each have degree programs running across multiple IU campuses.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The School of Medicine additionally has degree programs located at non-Indiana University system campuses, including but not limited to Purdue University's main campus in West Lafayette, Indiana State University in Terre Haute, and Ball State University in Muncie.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The Kelley School of Business, the Luddy School of Informatics, Computing, and Engineering, the O'Neil School of Public and Environmental Affairs, and the School of Education each have degree programs at the IU Bloomington and IU Indianapolis campuses.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The School of Nursing has degree programs at the IU Bloomington, IU Indianapolis, and IU Fort Wayne campuses.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Fairbanks School of Public Health has degree programs at the IU Indianapolis and IU Fort Wayne campuses.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] According to the National Association of College and University Business Officers (NACUBO), the value of the endowment of the Indiana University and affiliated foundation in 2016 is over $3.820 billion.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The annual budget across all campuses totals over $4.5 Billion.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The Indiana University Research and Technology Corporation (IURTC) is a not-for-profit agency that assists IU faculty and researchers in realizing the commercial potential of their discoveries.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Since 1997, university clients have been responsible for more than 1,800 inventions, nearly 500 patents, and 38 start-up companies.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In fiscal year 2016, the IURTC was issued 53 U.S. patents and 112 global patents.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In 1895, Marcellus Neal was the first African American to graduate and earn a degree (mathematics).
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In 1908, Clarence Augustus Lucas became the first African American to earn a Doctor of Medicine degree from the Indiana University School of Medicine.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In 1919, Frances Marshall was the first African-American woman to graduate from Indiana University (Bachelor of Arts (A.B.) degree in English).
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Thirty two years later in 1951, Richard Davis Johnson became the first African American faculty member when he was hired as a percussion instructor.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In 1975, Deborah Lynne McCullough and Beverly J.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Perkins became the first two African-American women to earn a doctor of medicine degree from Indiana University School of Medicine.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In April 2002, thousands of IU students and staff, along with Bloomington residents, rioted across the university campus before merging into adjacent city blocks after the IU men's basketball team lost the NCAA Basketball championship game to the University of Maryland Terrapins.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Rioters caused extensive damage to university buildings and city businesses, and at least 45 people were arrested during the riot.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights initiated a federal investigation of Indiana University's Title IX compliance, encompassing more than 450 sexual harassment and violence complaints filed with the university between 2011 and 2015.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The complaints involved both students and university staff or faculty.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The investigation revealed concerns with timeliness of response, lack of documentation, not preventing retaliation, and the creation of sexually hostile environments at the campus.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The investigation further criticized the lack of mandatory sexual harassment, misconduct, and awareness training for staff, as well as the lack of institutional support for its Title IX Coordinator to oversee compliance by the university.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The Fort Worth Police Department declined to press charges.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The university also charged the victim a dorm-relocation fee after the suspected rapist continued to harass the victim around her dormitory, which also went without intervention by the university.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The victim's case was also handled by former Title IX Director, Jason Casares prior to his resignation amidst sexual harassment and misconduct allegations as the university's student ethics director and Title IX deputy director.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In 2023, IU's Palestine Solidarity Committee held several protests against the Gaza war.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] IU's Student Government treasurer and co-director of DEI resigned after accusing other student government leadership members of antisemitism and failure to represent the whole student body.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The accused student body president responded by reaffirming the student government's commitment to fighting antisemitism and islamophobia and called the resignations part of "a historical pattern of undue criticism faced by Black women in positions of power." After learning of the controversy, U.S.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Representative Jim Banks sent a letter to university president Pamela Whitten demanding information about pro-Palestinian protests and alleged antisemitism on campus, identifying it as a violation of the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Banks threatened the continued federal funding for the university if the conduct was tolerated by the university administration.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Also in November 2023 the university barred a faculty member from teaching after alleging that he improperly assisted the Palestine Solidarity Committee, a student group, by reserving a room for them on campus.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Shortly thereafter, the university's administrators also cancelled a planned art exhibition by Samia Halaby, a Palestinian-American artist.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Critics viewed these actions as unjust attempts to deliver results in response to congressional scrutiny.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights again initiated a federal investigation of the university in response to a complaint of the violation of Title VI of the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The complaint alleged lack of response and complacency by the university administration to an increasing number of anti-Semitic incidents at the campus.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The ACLU of Indiana also sued IU, alleging that it had violated the First Amendment rights of people banned from campus after taking part in pro-Palestinian protests.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In April 2024, IU students and faculty joined other campuses across the US in protesting against the Gaza war and the accused genocide of Palestinians.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] IU president Pamela Whitten made allegations of 'antisemitic episodes'.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] National Guard and police in riot gear broke up the student encampment and multiple arrests were made.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The following academic year, after the administration brought in new policies to stop protests and limit "expressive activities", students and faculty held vigils for free speech and the Palestinian cause.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] In April 2025, an IU professor was investigated under Indiana's "intellectual diversity" law after an anonymous complaint that he had discussed his arrest during a civil disobedience action at the Israeli consulate.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] His tenure was threatened after an administrator escalated the complaint.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Both of the core campuses of the IU system sponsor NCAA Division I athletic programs.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The IU Indy Jaguars field 18 different sports, and have competed in the Horizon League since 2017; they were the IUPUI Jaguars before that school's dissolution.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Additionally, all but one of IU's regional campuses sponsors athletics within the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA).
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] The IU Northwest RedHawks and IU South Bend Titans compete as members of the Chicagoland Collegiate Athletic Conference, while the IU Columbus Crimson Pride, IU East Red Wolves, IU Kokomo Cougars, and IU Southeast Grenadiers compete as members of the River States Conference.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Indiana University has three medals to recognize individuals.
[src:indiana-university/indiana-university] Indiana University has several ways to recognize the accomplishments of faculty.
